public class Circle extends Shape {
    private final double radius;

    public Circle(double radius) {
        this.radius = radius;
    }

    @Override
    public double area() {
        return Math.PI * Math.pow(radius, 2);
    }
}
```
This code violates the Liskov Substitution Principle because it allows a subclass to violate the contract of its superclass. In this case, `Rectangle` and `Circle` both extend `Shape` but `Circle` overrides `area()` to return a negative value when given a negative radius, which is not possible in real-world scenarios.

The refactoring involves ensuring that the subclasses do not violate the contract of their superclass by adding validation checks or throwing exceptions if necessary. In this case, we could add a check for negative radii:

```java
public class Circle extends Shape {
    private final double radius;

    public Circle(double radius) {
        if (radius < 0) {
            throw new IllegalArgumentException("Radius must be non-negative");
        }
        this.radius = radius;
    }

    @Override
    public double area() {
        return Math.PI * Math.pow(radius, 2);
    }
}
```
Now `Circle` will always return a valid area value and the Liskov Substitution Principle is not violated.

